            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>There is no strict rule. Long-tail keywords are typically three or more words, but specificity and low search volume matter more than word count. A two-word phrase with 50 monthly searches and clear purchase intent functions as a long-tail keyword even without the word count.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Do long-tail keywords still work in 2026?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Yes. Long-tail keywords remain one of the most reliable SEO strategies, particularly with the growth of voice search, conversational AI queries, and Google's natural language understanding. Specificity is rewarded, not penalised.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Should I only target long-tail keywords?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>A balanced strategy works best. Long-tail keywords build authority, generate conversions, and compound into broader topical coverage over time. Use them to establish credibility in a niche, then expand into shorter, higher-volume terms as the site matures.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Can one page rank for multiple long-tail keywords?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Yes. Comprehensive, well-structured content often ranks for dozens or hundreds of related long-tail variations. Google's natural language understanding means a page targeting one specific phrase captures semantically similar queries without needing separate pages for each.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">What is the typical search volume range for a long-tail keyword?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Most long-tail keywords have between 10 and 1,000 monthly searches per keyword. The aggregate value comes from targeting many of them across a content strategy, not from high individual volume.</p></div></div>
          </div>
